<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Transfers Nuclear Warheads to Russia Amid Fuel Controversy </TI></H3>
<H4>   First 60 Warheads En Route to Sverdlovsk Region </H4>
<F P=102> LD0503121594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1106 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0503121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The first train carrying 60 nuclear warheads, 
removed from the Ukrainian strategic missiles, left the railway 
station of Pervomaisk at 19:42 on March 4 and headed to Russia, 
an informed source in the Russian Defense Ministry told 
Interfax. He said that at 12:00, Saturday, the train was near 
the city of Poltava in Ukraine. 
  The same source said that the nuclear warheads would be 
taken 
to the Sverdlovsk Region, where they would be disassembled. He 
also pointed out that a second train would be sent to Russia 
from the city of Khmelnitskiy in the middle of March. 
  There are a total of about 2,000 nuclear warheads in 
Ukraine's 46th missile division (Pervomaisk) and the 43rd 
missile brigade (Khmelnitskiy). 

</TEXT>

