<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Transfers Nuclear Warheads to Russia Amid Fuel Controversy </TI></H3>
<H4>   Vice Premier Declines Comment On Second Shipment </H4>
<F P=102> LD0903205894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1942 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Vice Prime Minister Valeriy Shmarov 
declined to confirm reports that a second train loaded with 
nuclear munitions had left Ukraine for Russia on March 9. 
  "Information of this kind is extremely confidential as 
shipping such freights entails necessary security measures," he 
told Interfax-Ukraine. 
  "It would be desirable if people handling these processes on 
both sides did not create tense situations in future," Shmarov 
said. He added that "professionals did their best to ensure the 
security of the shipment and make sure the freight arrives at 
its destination by the shortest possible route." 
  Ukraine has not received nuclear fuel from Russia as 
envisioned in the trilateral statement by the U.S., Ukrainian 
and Russian presidents. The only thing the Ukrainian leadership 
received was a telegram from Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin stating that the Russian government would start the 
supplies before the end of this month. 

</TEXT>

