<H3> <TI>   Senior Officials Comment on General's Arrest for Heroin Trafficking </TI></H3>
<H4>   Prasong: Consulate To Assist Thanat </H4>
<F P=102> 94WD0196A Bangkok SIAM RAT in Thai 12 Dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0196A </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok SIAM RAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Excerpts] Squadron Leader Prasong Sunsiri, the minister of 
foreign affairs, said that he had received a report from the 
Thai consul general in Hong Kong regarding the arrest of an army 
officer on narcotics charges. He has ordered the Thai consulate 
to coordinate things, help find a lawyer, and provide other help. 
  Hong Kong police officials and U.S. DEA [Drug Enforcement 
Administration] officials arrested Major General Thanat 
Phakpadiphat, who is assigned to the Supreme Command, in Hong 
Kong on charges of trafficking in heroin. 
  The minister of foreign affairs, who was interviewed by 
reporters before leaving on a trip to Cambodia on 11 December, 
said that he has not been contacted by Major General Thanat. If 
it is found that he actually was involved in illegal activities, 
resolute action must be taken in accord with the law. As for 
whether he will be extradited to the United States for trial, 
that depends on the extradition treaty between the United States 
and Hong Kong. [passage omitted] 
  In an interview, General Wichit Sukmak, the minister of 
defense, said that Major General Thanat's arrest by DEA 
officials in Hong Kong is a personal matter and will not affect 
the Army's image. 

</TEXT>

