<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> VIETNAM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Customs Inspector Uncovers Attempt To Mail 3 Kg of Morphine to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2402100294 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1100 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2402100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to sources from the antismuggling 
department under the Customs General Department, customs 
officers at the Ho Chi Minh City postal service have uncovered a 
case of drug trafficking through the postal service as follows: 
  While checking a parcel destined for the United States, 
Customs Inspector Le Dinh Khang discovered that the liner of a 
blanket contained a layer of morphine. The liner itself was fit 
into a quilt. The overall weight of the blanket was 5.95 
kilograms and the layer of morphine alone weighed about 3 
kilograms. The name of the sender was Tran Thi Quang Kim, a 
resident of Thong Nhat District in Dong Nai Province, and the 
name of the receiver was Ly Quang Minh, an overseas Vietnamese 
in the United States. It was also known that Nong Thi Kim Dung, 
a resident of Ba Ria-Vung Tau, brought the parcel to the post 
office. 
  Both the proof of the crime and the persons involved have 
already been handed over to the Ho Chi Minh public security 
service for further investigation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

