<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Counternarcotics Official Details Recent Seizures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2002195894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1810 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2002195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 20 Feb (MENA)--The Counternarcotics agencies 
at the Cairo Security Directorate have succeeded in the past 
four months in seizing 67 kg of hashish and four kg of heroin, 
estimated at 1.4 million pounds, 500 grams of opium, and four kg 
of various types of narcotic pills. Brigadier General 'Abdallah 
al-Watiri, head of the Counternarcotics Department at the Cairo 
Security Directorate, said today that the Counternarcotics 
Department succeeded in the past nine months in eliminating most 
drug trafficking dens in Cairo, particularly the areas of 
al-Batniyah, al-Jayyarah, al-Husayniyah, and Birkat al-Hajj. 
  Al-Watiri said that the intensive campaigns by 
counternarcotics personnel led to the seizure of a number of 
kiosks that sell the bango plant, which is a cheap drug compared 
to other types. The price of one kilogram of bango ranges from 
600 to 900 pounds, whereas one kilo of heroin sells for 400,000 
pounds. He noted that campaigns were launched against certain 
pharmacies, which resulted in the closure of many pharmacies 
that trade illegally in certain medicines and tranquilizers that 
contain narcotic and alcoholic ingredients. The Health Ministry 
and the Pharmacists Association have been notified. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

