<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   MIR Links With Drug Traffickers, Members' Withdrawal Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2802154194 La Paz Radio Fides Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2802154194 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Radio Fides Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ricardo Diaz from Sucre] </F>
  [Text] The strong party structure of the Movement of the 
Revolutionary Left, MIR, and of the Nationalist Democratic 
Action, ADN, is silently crumbling as the result of the 
withdrawal of several of their members. The crisis became more 
acute following the dissemination of charges about alleged links 
between high-ranking MIR leaders--including [former Bolivian 
President] Jaime Paz Zamora--with drug traffickers. MIR and ADN 
congressmen have been observed to maintain a discreet silence 
over the issue, thus causing the two parties middle-ranking 
leaders' to leave the parties' ranks. 
  ADN leader Gaston Encina, who was previously one of the main 
MIR defenders, does not want to comment on the issue and is 
withdrawing from the political scenario. The public, however, 
would like to hear his opinion because it is known that he also 
participated in the meetings with drug traffickers, as the 
charges state. 
  The crisis is affecting not only former President Jaime Paz 
Zamora's party; it has also stained Mr. Hugo Banzer Suarez' 
party. In the last few hours, the withdrawal of several ADN 
members and middle-ranking leaders has been reported. Among the 
withdrawing ADN members is Jorge Landivar Rua, a former 
Chuquisaca Department ADN governor. He said: We have been 
fighting corruption and are now indignant that trafficking may 
have permeated the national structure of our political parties. 
I bluntly repudiate the situation because these links, 
particularly MIR links, with drug trafficking are twofold 
corrupt, Landivar said. 
  The MIR and ADN crisis is becoming more acute. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

