<H3> <TI>   Former President's Secretary Denies Report of Arrest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0403202194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1824 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0403202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] La Paz, 4 Mar (EFE) -- The private secretary of 
former Bolivian President Jaime Paz Zamora today denied to EFE 
that she had been arrested by Special Antinarcotics Force 
(FELCN) members. 
  During a telephone conversation with EFE, Susana Seleme said 
from her home in Santa Cruz, 851 km east of La Paz, that she had 
never been arrested and that the FELCN had not summoned her to 
testify. 
  Radio Panamericana of La Paz today said that Seleme had been 
arrested for alleged links with drug trafficking. 
  Interior Minister German Quiroga did not want either to 
confirm or deny the arrest of Seleme because, he said, it is 
"confidential information." 
  In statements to Radio Panamericana, Quiroga also did not 
confirm or deny that an arrest warrant has been issued against 
other leaders in Paz Zamora's party, the Movement of the 
Revolutionary Left (MIR). 

</TEXT>

