<H3> <TI>   Southwestern Goias Described As `Gateway' for New Drug Trafficking Route </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0229B Brasilia CORREIO BRAZILIENSE in Portuguese 26 Jan 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0229B </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia CORREIO BRAZILIENSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article: "PF Intensifies Drug Fight in Goias"] </F>
  [Text] Goiania--As the gateway in a new drug trafficking 
route, the southwestern part of Goias--bordering on Mato 
Grosso--is going to be the target of a Federal Police sweep. The 
seizure of a shipment of 198 kg of cocaine in the municipality 
of Aparecida do Rio Doce (in southwestern Goias) early last 
Saturday morning provided the PF [Federal Police] with 
confirmation that Goias is part of the international traffic's 
network of routes and that it is being used to transport drugs 
from Bolivia on their way to destinations abroad. Although the 
198 kg of cocaine in question constitute the largest drug 
seizure ever in that state, PF Police Chief Leone Oliveira, who 
was in charge of the operation, estimates that the amount in 
question represents less than 5 percent of the total passing 
through the region every month. 
  The drug, which was found in false bottoms built into two 
stake trucks of the kind used to carry cattle, is now at the 
Federal Police Superintendency in Goiania, where it will be 
incinerated as soon as court authorization is received. The 
drivers of the two trucks, Domingos Donizeth Vilani, 37, and 
Moises Fernandes Maciel, 33, are now in custody. 

</TEXT>

